e=3D"display:none">Type of formal logic</div>
<p>
<b>Modal logic</b> is a kind of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lo=
gic" title=3D"Logic">logic</a> used to represent statements about <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modality_(natural_language)" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Modality (natural language)">necessity and possibility</=
a>. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy" title=3D"Philos=
ophy">philosophy</a> and related fields
it is used as a tool for understanding concepts such as <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knowledge" title=3D"Knowledge">knowledge</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Obligation" title=3D"Obligation">obligati=
on</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causality" title=3D"Ca=
usality">causation</a>. For instance, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Epistemic_modal_logic" title=3D"Epistemic modal logic">epistemic mod=
al logic</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Well-formed_form=
ula" title=3D"Well-formed formula">formula</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-elem=
