<p>The different systems of modal logic are defined using <i>frame conditio=
ns</i>. A frame is called:
</p>
<ul><li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reflexive_relation" tit=
le=3D"Reflexive relation">reflexive</a></b> if <i>w R w</i>, for every <i>w=
</i> in <i>G</i></li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_relation" title=
=3D"Symmetric relation">symmetric</a></b> if <i>w R u</i> implies <i>u R w<=
/i>, for all <i>w</i> and <i>u</i> in <i>G</i></li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transitive_relation" title=
=3D"Transitive relation">transitive</a></b> if <i>w R u</i> and <i>u R q</i=
> together imply <i>w R q</i>, for all <i>w</i>, <i>u</i>, <i>q</i> in <i>G=
</i>.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Serial_relation" title=3D"S=
erial relation">serial</a></b> if, for every <i>w</i> in <i>G</i> there is =
some <i>u</i> in <i>G</i> such that <i>w R u</i>.</li>
<li><b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_relation" title=
=3D"Euclidean relation">Euclidean</a></b> if, for every <i>u</i>, <i>t</i>,=
 and <i>w</i>, <i>w R u</i> and <i>w R t</i> implies <i>u R t</i> (by symme=
try, it also implies <i>t R u</i>, as well as <i>t R t</i> and <i>u R u</i>=
)</li></ul>
<p>The logics that system from these frame conditions are:
</p>
<ul><li><i>K</i>&nbsp;:=3D no conditions</li>
<li><i>D</i>&nbsp;:=3D serial</li>
<li><i>T</i>&nbsp;:=3D reflexive</li>
<li><i>B</i>&nbsp;:=3D reflexive and symmetric</li>
<li><i>S4</i>&nbsp;:=3D <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preorder" =
title=3D"Preorder">reflexive and transitive</a></li>
<li><i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S5_(modal_logic)" title=3D"=
S5 (modal logic)">S5</a></i>&nbsp;:=3D reflexive and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_relation" title=3D"Euclidean relation">Euclide=
an</a></li></ul>
<p>The Euclidean property along with reflexivity yields symmetry and transi=
tivity. (The Euclidean property can be obtained, as well, from symmetry and=
 transitivity.) Hence if the accessibility relation <i>R</i> is reflexive a=
nd Euclidean, <i>R</i> is provably <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Symmetric_relation" title=3D"Symmetric relation">symmetric</a> and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transitive_relation" title=3D"Transitive =
relation">transitive</a> as well. Hence for models of S5, <i>R</i> is an <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_relation" title=3D"Equiv=
alence relation">equivalence relation</a>, because <i>R</i> is reflexive, s=
ymmetric and transitive.
</p><p>We can prove that these frames produce the same set of valid sentenc=
