<p>Topological approaches subsume relational ones, allowing <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-normal_modal_logic" title=3D"Non-normal modal=
 logic">non-normal modal logics</a>. The extra structure they provide also =
allows a transparent way of modeling certain concepts such as the evidence =
or justification one has for one's beliefs. Topological semantics is widely=
 used in recent work in formal epistemology and has antecedents in earlier =
work such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Lewis_(philosop=
her)" title=3D"David Lewis (philosopher)">David Lewis</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angelika_Kratzer" title=3D"Angelika Kratzer">An=
gelika Kratzer</a>'s logics for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
unterfactuals" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Counterfactuals">counterfactu=
als</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Axiomatic_systems">Axiomati=
c systems</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMo=
dal_logic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Axiomat=
ic systems"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Diagram_of_Normal_Modal_Logics.png" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/thumb/b/bd/Diagram_of_Normal_Modal_Logics.png/250px-Diagram_of_Normal_=
Modal_Logics.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"317" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"520" data-file-height=3D"660"></a><figc=
aption>Diagram of common modal logics; <b>K4W</b> stands for <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Provability_logic" title=3D"Provability logic">P=
rovability logic</a>, and <b>B</b> on the top corner stands for <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L._E._J._Brouwer" title=3D"L. E. J. Brouwer">=
Brouwer</a>'s system of <b>KTB</b></figcaption></figure>
<p>The first formalizations of modal logic were <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Axiomatic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Axiomatic">axiomati=
c</a>. Numerous variations with very different properties have been propose=
d since <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._I._Lewis" title=3D"C. I=
. Lewis">C. I. Lewis</a> began working in the area in 1912. <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Edward_Hughes" title=3D"George Edward Hugh=
es">Hughes</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_John_Cressw=
ell" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Max John Cresswell">Cresswell</a> (1996=
), for example, describe 42 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal=
_modal_logic" title=3D"Normal modal logic">normal</a> and 25 non-normal mod=
al logics. Zeman (1973) describes some systems Hughes and Cresswell omit.
</p><p>Modern treatments of modal logic begin by augmenting the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Propositional calculus">propositional calculus</a> with two unary=
 operations, one denoting "necessity" and the other "possibility". The nota=
tion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarence_Irving_Lewis" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Clarence Irving Lewis">C. I. Lewis</a>, much em=
ployed since, denotes "necessarily <i>p</i>" by a prefixed "box" (=E2=96=A1=
<i>p</i>) whose <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scope_(logic)" tit=
le=3D"Scope (logic)">scope</a> is established by parentheses. Likewise, a p=
refixed "diamond" (=E2=97=87<i>p</i>) denotes "possibly <i>p</i>". Similar =
to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantifier_(logic)" title=
=3D"Quantifier (logic)">quantifiers</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/First-order_logic" title=3D"First-order logic">first-order logic</=
a>, "necessarily <i>p</i>" (=E2=96=A1<i>p</i>) does not assume the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantifier_(logic)#Range_of_quantificatio=
n" title=3D"Quantifier (logic)">range of quantification</a> (the set of acc=
essible possible worlds in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kripke_=
semantics" title=3D"Kripke semantics">Kripke semantics</a>) to be non-empty=
, whereas "possibly <i>p</i>" (=E2=97=87<i>p</i>) often implicitly assumes =
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe=
-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xm=
lns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \Diamo=
nd \top }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=E2=97=8A<!-- =E2=97=8A --></mi>
        <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=E2=8A=A4<!-- =E2=8A=A4 --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \Diamond \top=
 }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c74330f49fbaf2a49ea238aad8ca6092ec0c119e" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.505ex; width:3.358ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \Di=
amond \top }"></span> (viz. the set of accessible possible worlds is non-em=
pty). Regardless of notation, each of these operators is definable in terms=
 of the other in classical modal logic:
</p>
<ul><li>=E2=96=A1<i>p</i> (necessarily <i>p</i>) is equivalent to <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml">=C2=AC=E2=97=87=C2=AC<i>p</i></span> ("not possible that not=
-<i>p</i>")</li>
<li>=E2=97=87<i>p</i> (possibly <i>p</i>) is equivalent to <span class=3D"t=
exhtml">=C2=AC=E2=96=A1=C2=AC<i>p</i></span> ("not necessarily not-<i>p</i>=
")</li></ul>
<p>Hence =E2=96=A1 and =E2=97=87 form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Duality_(mathematics)#Duality_in_logic_and_set_theory" title=3D"Duali=
ty (mathematics)">dual pair</a> of operators.
</p><p>In many modal logics, the necessity and possibility operators satisf=
y the following analogues of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Mo=
rgan%27s_laws" title=3D"De Morgan's laws">de Morgan's laws</a> from <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(logic)" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Boolean algebra (logic)">Boolean algebra</a>:
</p>
<dl><dd>"It is <b>not necessary that</b> <i>X</i>" is <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logical_equivalence" title=3D"Logical equivalence">logi=
cally equivalent</a> to "It is <b>possible that not</b> <i>X</i>".</dd>
<dd>"It is <b>not possible that</b> <i>X</i>" is logically equivalent to "I=
t is <b>necessary that not</b> <i>X</i>".</dd></dl>
<p>Precisely what axioms and rules must be added to the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Propositional calculus">propositional calculus</a> to create a usable s=
ystem of modal logic is a matter of philosophical opinion, often driven by =
the theorems one wishes to prove; or, in computer science, it is a matter o=
f what sort of computational or deductive system one wishes to model. Many =
modal logics, known collectively as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Normal_modal_logic" title=3D"Normal modal logic">normal modal logics</a>,=
 include the following rule and axiom:<span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Necessit=
ation_rule"></span>
</p>
<ul><li><b>N</b>, <b>Necessitation Rule</b>: If <i>p</i> is a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theorem" title=3D"Theorem">theorem</a>/<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tautology_(logic)" title=3D"Tautology (lo=
gic)">tautology</a> (of any system/model invoking <b>N</b>), then =E2=96=A1=
<i>p</i> is likewise a theorem (i.e. <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-ma=
th-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a1=
1y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Mat=
hML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (\models p)\implies (\models \Box p)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mo>=E2=8A=A8<!-- =E2=8A=A8 --></mo>
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=9F=B9<!-- =E2=9F=B9 --></mo>
        <mspace width=3D"thickmathspace"></mspace>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mo>=E2=8A=A8<!-- =E2=8A=A8 --></mo>
        <mi>=E2=97=BB<!-- =E2=97=BB --></mi>
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle (\models p)\i=
mplies (\models \Box p)}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/89c953c2327c499bfb82bc79a149a204f0434bcc" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:19.472ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (\=
models p)\implies (\models \Box p)}"></span>).</li>
<li><b>K</b>, <b>Distribution Axiom</b>: <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=96=A1(=
<i>p</i> =E2=86=92 <i>q</i>) =E2=86=92 (=E2=96=A1<i>p</i> =E2=86=92 =E2=96=
=A1<i>q</i>).</span></li></ul>
<p>The weakest <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_modal_logic"=
 title=3D"Normal modal logic">normal modal logic</a>, named "<i>K</i>" in h=
onor of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Kripke" title=3D"Saul=
 Kripke">Saul Kripke</a>, is simply the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Propositional_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Propositional =
calculus">propositional calculus</a> augmented by =E2=96=A1, the rule <b>N<=
/b>, and the axiom <b>K</b>. <i>K</i> is weak in that it fails to determine=
 whether a proposition can be necessary but only contingently necessary. Th=
at is, it is not a theorem of <i>K</i> that if =E2=96=A1<i>p</i> is true th=
en =E2=96=A1=E2=96=A1<i>p</i> is true, i.e., that necessary truths are "nec=
essarily necessary". If such perplexities are deemed forced and artificial,=
 this defect of <i>K</i> is not a great one. In any case, different answers=
 to such questions yield different systems of modal logic.
</p><p>Adding axioms to <i>K</i> gives rise to other well-known modal syste=
ms. One cannot prove in <i>K</i> that if "<i>p</i> is necessary" then <i>p<=
/i> is true. The axiom <b>T</b> remedies this defect:
</p>
<ul><li><b>T</b>, <b>Reflexivity Axiom</b>: <span class=3D"texhtml">=E2=96=
=A1<i>p</i> =E2=86=92 <i>p</i></span> (If <i>p</i> is necessary, then <i>p<=
/i> is the case.)</li></ul>
<p><b>T</b> holds in most but not all modal logics. Zeman (1973) describes =
a few exceptions, such as <i>S1<sup>0</sup></i>.
</p><p>Other well-known elementary axioms are:
</p>
<ul><li><b>4</b>: <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline">=
<span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"displa=
