P{\text{ and }}{\mathsf {G}}P}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/d85353ab6d2d9b69a64110f4bcf7aaa34d6ebd0d" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:17.656ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \B=
ox _{2}P=3DP{\text{ and }}{\mathsf {G}}P}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>The operators <b>F</b> and <b>G</b> may seem initially foreign, but they=
 create <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_modal_logic" title=
=3D"Normal modal logic">normal modal systems</a>. <b>F</b><i>P</i> is the s=
ame as =C2=AC<b>G</b>=C2=AC<i>P</i>. We can combine the above operators to =
form complex statements. For example, <b>P</b><i>P</i> =E2=86=92 =E2=96=A1<=
b>P</b><i>P</i> says (effectively), <i>Everything that is past and true is =
necessary</i>.
</p><p>It seems reasonable to say that possibly it will rain tomorrow, and =
possibly it will not; on the other hand, since we cannot change the past, i=
f it is true that it rained yesterday, it cannot be true that it may not ha=
ve rained yesterday. It seems the past is "fixed", or necessary, in a way t=
he future is not. This is sometimes referred to as <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Accidental_necessity" title=3D"Accidental necessity">accid=
ental necessity</a>. But if the past is "fixed", and everything that is in =
the future will eventually be in the past, then it seems plausible to say t=
hat future events are necessary too.
</p><p>Similarly, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_f=
uture_contingents" title=3D"Problem of future contingents">problem of futur=
e contingents</a> considers the semantics of assertions about the future: i=
s either of the propositions 'There will be a sea battle tomorrow', or 'The=
re will not be a sea battle tomorrow' now true? Considering this thesis led=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" title=3D"Aristotle">Ar=
istotle</a> to reject the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principl=
e_of_bivalence" title=3D"Principle of bivalence">principle of bivalence</a>=
 for assertions concerning the future.
</p><p>Additional binary operators are also relevant to temporal logics (se=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_temporal_logic" title=3D"=
Linear temporal logic">Linear temporal logic</a>).
</p><p>Versions of temporal logic can be used in <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer scienc=
e</a> to model computer operations and prove theorems about them. In one ve=
rsion, =E2=97=87<i>P</i> means "at a future time in the computation it is p=
ossible that the computer state will be such that <i>P</i> is true"; =E2=96=
=A1<i>P</i> means "at all future times in the computation P will be true". =
In another version, =E2=97=87<i>P</i> means "at the immediate next state of=
 the computation, <i>P</i> might be true"; =E2=96=A1<i>P</i> means "at the =
immediate next state of the computation, <i>P</i> will be true". These diff=
er in the choice of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility_=
relation" title=3D"Accessibility relation">Accessibility relation</a>. (<i>=
P</i> always means "<i>P</i> is true at the current computer state".) These=
 two examples involve nondeterministic or not-fully-understood computations=
; there are many other modal logics specialized to different types of progr=
am analysis. Each one naturally leads to slightly different axioms.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Deontic_logic">Deontic logi=
c</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModal_logi=
c&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit section: Deontic logic"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deontic_logic" title=
=3D"Deontic logic">Deontic logic</a></div>
<p>Likewise talk of morality, or of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Obligation" title=3D"Obligation">obligation</a> and <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norm_(philosophy)" title=3D"Norm (philosophy)">norms</a=
> generally, seems to have a modal structure. The difference between "You m=
ust do this" and "You may do this" looks a lot like the difference between =
"This is necessary" and "This is possible". Such logics are called <i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deontic_logic" title=3D"Deontic logic">=
deontic</a></i>, from the Greek for "duty".
</p><p>Deontic logics commonly lack the axiom <b>T</b> semantically corresp=
onding to the reflexivity of the accessibility relation in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kripke_semantics" title=3D"">Kripke semantics</a>:=
 in symbols, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: no=
ne;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displa=
ystyle \Box \phi \to \phi }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=E2=97=BB<!-- =E2=97=BB --></mi>
        <mi>=CF=95<!-- =CF=95 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=CF=95<!-- =CF=95 --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \Box \phi \to=
 \phi }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/6a5d644484623825d62865ca86260267c2d404b6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:8.193ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \Bo=
x \phi \to \phi }"></span>. Interpreting =E2=96=A1 as "it is obligatory tha=
t", <b>T</b> informally says that every obligation is true. For example, if=
 it is obligatory not to kill others (i.e. killing is morally forbidden), t=
hen <b>T</b> implies that people actually do not kill others. The consequen=
t is obviously false.
</p><p>Instead, using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kripke_seman=
tics" title=3D"Kripke semantics">Kripke semantics</a>, we say that though o=
ur own world does not realize all obligations, the worlds accessible to it =
do (i.e., <b>T</b> holds at these worlds). These worlds are called <i>ideal=
ized</i> worlds. <i>P</i> is obligatory with respect to our own world if at=
 all idealized worlds accessible to our world, <i>P</i> holds. Though this =
was one of the first interpretations of the formal semantics, it has recent=
ly come under criticism.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One other principle that is often (at least traditionally) accepted =
as a deontic principle is <i>D</i>, <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-mat=
h-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11=
y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \Box \phi \to \Diamond \phi }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>=E2=97=BB<!-- =E2=97=BB --></mi>
        <mi>=CF=95<!-- =CF=95 --></mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">=E2=86=92<!-- =E2=86=92 --></mo>
        <mi>=E2=97=8A<!-- =E2=97=8A --></mi>
        <mi>=CF=95<!-- =CF=95 --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \Box \phi \to=
 \Diamond \phi }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/63cbbc101c379e0a4724342afd4a3e41f3fb0bd7" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:9.743ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \Bo=
x \phi \to \Diamond \phi }"></span>, which corresponds to the seriality (or=
 extendability or unboundedness) of the accessibility relation. It is an em=
bodiment of the Kantian idea that "ought implies can". (Clearly the "can" c=
an be interpreted in various senses, e.g. in a moral or alethic sense.)
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Intuitive_problems_with_deo=
ntic_logic">Intuitive problems with deontic logic</h4><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModal_logic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sec=
tion=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Intuitive problems with deontic logic"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<p>When we try to formalize ethics with standard modal logic, we run into s=
ome problems. Suppose that we have a proposition <i>K</i>: you have stolen =
some money, and another, <i>Q</i>: you have stolen a small amount of money.=
 Now suppose we want to express the thought that "if you have stolen some m=
oney, it ought to be a small amount of money". There are two likely candida=
tes,
</p>
<dl><dd>(1) <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span =
class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: non=
