<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Doxastic_logic">Doxastic lo=
gic</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModal_lo=
gic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Doxastic log=
ic"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Doxastic_logic" titl=
e=3D"Doxastic logic">Doxastic logic</a></div>
<p><i>Doxastic logic</i> concerns the logic of belief (of some set of agent=
s). The term doxastic is derived from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> <i>doxa</i=
> which means "belief". Typically, a doxastic logic uses =E2=96=A1, often w=
ritten "B", to mean "It is believed that", or when relativized to a particu=
lar agent s, "It is believed by s that".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Extensions">Extensions</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModal_logic&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Extensions"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Modal logics may be extended to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Fuzzy_logic" title=3D"Fuzzy logic">fuzzy form</a> with calculi in the clas=
s of fuzzy Kripke models.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-18"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Modal logics may also be enhanced via <i>base-extension semantics</i=
> for the classical propositional systems. In this case, the validity of a =
formula can be shown by an inductive definition generated by provability in=
 a =E2=80=98base=E2=80=99 of atomic rules.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-1=
9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
=E2=81=A0
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intuitionistic_logic" title=
=3D"Intuitionistic logic">Intuitionistic</a> modal logics are used in diffe=
rent areas of application, and they have often risen from different sources=
. The areas include the foundations of mathematics, computer science and ph=
ilosophy. In these approaches, often modalities are added to intuitionistic=
 logic to create new intuitionistic connectives and to simulate the monadic=
 elements of intuitionistic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_=
order_logic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"First order logic">first order =
logic</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Metaphysical_questions">Met=
aphysical questions</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DModal_logic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Metaphysical questions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessibility=
_relation" title=3D"Accessibility relation">Accessibility relation</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Possible_worlds" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Possible worlds">Possible worlds</a></div>
<p>In the most common interpretation of modal logic, one considers "<a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logically_possible" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Logically possible">logically possible</a> worlds". If a statemen=
t is true in all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Possible_worlds" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Possible worlds">possible worlds</a>, then i=
t is a necessary truth. If a statement happens to be true in our world, but=
 is not true in all possible worlds, then it is a contingent truth. A state=
ment that is true in some possible world (not necessarily our own) is calle=
d a possible truth.
</p><p>Under this "possible worlds idiom", to maintain that Bigfoot's exist=
ence is possible but not actual, one says, "There is some possible world in=
 which Bigfoot exists; but in the actual world, Bigfoot does not exist". Ho=
wever, it is unclear what this claim commits us to. Are we really alleging =
the existence of possible worlds, every bit as real as our actual world, ju=
st not actual? <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Kripke" title=
=3D"Saul Kripke">Saul Kripke</a> believes that 'possible world' is somethin=
g of a misnomer =E2=80=93 that the term 'possible world' is just a useful w=
ay of visualizing the concept of possibility.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_no=
te-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> For him, the sentences "you could have rolled a 4 instea=
d of a 6" and "there is a possible world where you rolled a 4, but you roll=
ed a 6 in the actual world" are not significantly different statements, and=
 neither commit us to the existence of a possible world.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_log=
ic#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David=
_Lewis_(philosopher)" title=3D"David Lewis (philosopher)">David Lewis</a>, =
on the other hand, made himself notorious by biting the bullet, asserting t=
hat all merely possible worlds are as real as our own, and that what distin=
guishes our world as <i>actual</i> is simply that it is indeed our world =
=E2=80=93 <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indexicality" title=
=3D"Indexicality">this</a></i> world.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-23"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> That position is a major tenet of "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Modal_realism" title=3D"Modal realism">modal realism</a>". Some =
philosophers decline to endorse any version of modal realism, considering i=
t ontologically extravagant, and prefer to seek various ways to paraphrase =
away these ontological commitments. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Robert_Merrihew_Adams" title=3D"Robert Merrihew Adams">Robert Adams</a> h=
olds that 'possible worlds' are better thought of as 'world-stories', or co=
nsistent sets of propositions. Thus, it is possible that you rolled a 4 if =
such a state of affairs can be described coherently.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#c=
ite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Computer scientists will generally pick a highly specific interpreta=
tion of the modal operators specialized to the particular sort of computati=
on being analysed. In place of "all worlds", you may have "all possible nex=
t states of the computer", or "all possible future states of the computer".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Further_applications">Furth=
er applications</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DModal_logic&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: =
Further applications"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Modal logics have begun to be used in areas of the humanities such as li=
terature, poetry, art and history.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-25"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philosophy_of_religion" title=3D"Philosophy of r=
eligion">philosophy of religion</a>, modal logics are commonly used in argu=
ments for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Existence_of_God" ti=
tle=3D"Existence of God">existence of God</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_no=
te-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DModal_logic&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The basic ideas of modal logic date back to antiquity. <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" title=3D"Aristotle">Aristotle</a> develo=
ped a modal syllogistic in Book I of his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Prior_Analytics" title=3D"Prior Analytics">Prior Analytics</a></i=
> (ch. 8=E2=80=9322), which <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theoph=
rastus" title=3D"Theophrastus">Theophrastus</a> attempted to improve.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Modal_logic#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There are also passages in Aristo=
tle's work, such as the famous <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro=
blem_of_future_contingents" title=3D"Problem of future contingents">sea-bat=
tle argument</a> in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/De_Interpre=
tatione" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"De Interpretatione">De Interpretati=
one</a></i> =C2=A79, that are now seen as anticipations of the connection o=
f modal logic with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Potentiality" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Potentiality">potentiality</a> and time. In t=
he Hellenistic period, the logicians <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Diodorus_Cronus" title=3D"Diodorus Cronus">Diodorus Cronus</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philo_the_Dialectician" title=3D"Philo th=
e Dialectician">Philo the Dialectician</a> and the Stoic <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chrysippus" title=3D"Chrysippus">Chrysippus</a> each=
 developed a modal system that accounted for the interdefinability of possi=
bility and necessity, accepted <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axi=
om" title=3D"Axiom">axiom</a> <b>T</b> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Modal_logic#Axiomatic_systems">=C2=A7&nbsp;Axiomatic systems</a>)=
, and combined elements of modal logic and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Temporal_logic" title=3D"Temporal logic">temporal logic</a> in att=
empts to solve the notorious <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diodo=
rus_Cronus#Master_argument" title=3D"Diodorus Cronus">Master Argument</a>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The earliest formal system o=
f modal logic was developed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avi=
cenna" title=3D"Avicenna">Avicenna</a>, who ultimately developed a theory o=
f "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_logic" title=3D"Tempor=
al logic">temporally</a> modal" syllogistic.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Britannica_=
30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_lo=
gic#cite_note-Britannica-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Modal logic as a self-aware subjec=
t owes much to the writings of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Scholastics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scholastics">Scholastics</a>, =
in particular <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_of_Ockham" t=
itle=3D"William of Ockham">William of Ockham</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Duns_Scotus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"John Du=
ns Scotus">John Duns Scotus</a>, who reasoned informally in a modal manner,=
 mainly to analyze statements about <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Essence" title=3D"Essence">essence</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Accident_(philosophy)" title=3D"Accident (philosophy)">accident<=
/a>.
</p><p>In the 19th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hugh_M=
acColl" title=3D"Hugh MacColl">Hugh MacColl</a> made innovative contributio=
ns to modal logic, but did not find much acknowledgment.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_log=
ic#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._I.=
_Lewis" title=3D"C. I. Lewis">C. I. Lewis</a> founded modern modal logic in=
 a series of scholarly articles beginning in 1912 with "Implication and the=
 Algebra of Logic".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Modal_logic#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Lewis was led to invent modal logi=
c, and specifically <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strict_implica=
tion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Strict implication">strict implication=
</a>, on the grounds that classical logic grants <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Paradoxes_of_material_implication" title=3D"Paradoxes of mat=
erial implication">paradoxes of material implication</a> such as the princi=
ple that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vacuous_truth" title=3D"V=
acuous truth">a falsehood implies any proposition</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic=
#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> This work culminated in his 1932 book <i>Symboli=
c Logic</i> (with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooper_Harold_La=
ngford" title=3D"Cooper Harold Langford">C. H. Langford</a>),<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moda=
l_logic#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which introduced the five systems <i>S1</=
i> through <i>S5</i>.
</p><p>After Lewis, modal logic received little attention for several decad=
es. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicholas_Rescher" title=3D"Nic=
holas Rescher">Nicholas Rescher</a> has argued that this was because <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bertrand_Russell" title=3D"Bertrand Russ=
ell">Bertrand Russell</a> rejected it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-36"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> However, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DJan_Dejnozka&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"J=
an Dejnozka (page does not exist)">Jan Dejnozka</a> has argued against this=
 view, stating that a modal system which Dejnozka calls "MDL" is described =
in Russell's works, although Russell did believe the concept of modality to=
 "come from confusing propositions with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Propositional_function" title=3D"Propositional function">propositiona=
l functions</a>", as he wrote in <i>The Analysis of Matter</i>.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mo=
dal_logic#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Ruth C. Barcan (later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruth_=
Barcan_Marcus" title=3D"Ruth Barcan Marcus">Ruth Barcan Marcus</a>) develop=
ed the first axiomatic systems of quantified modal logic =E2=80=94 first an=
d second order extensions of Lewis' <i>S2</i>, <i>S4</i>, and <i>S5</i>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-38" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-39" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_no=
te-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-40" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-40"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Norman_Prior" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Arthur Norman Prior">Arthur Norman Prior</a> warned her to prepa=
re well in the debates concerning quantified modal logic with <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willard_Van_Orman_Quine" title=3D"Willard Van O=
rman Quine">Willard Van Orman Quine</a>, because of bias against modal logi=
c.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-41" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The contemporary era in modal semantics began in 1959, when <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saul_Kripke" title=3D"Saul Kripke">Saul K=
ripke</a> (then only a 18-year-old <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Harvard_University" title=3D"Harvard University">Harvard University</a> un=
dergraduate) introduced the now-standard <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Kripke_semantics" title=3D"Kripke semantics">Kripke semantics</a> fo=
r modal logics. These are commonly referred to as "possible worlds" semanti=
cs. Kripke and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._N._Prior" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"A. N. Prior">A. N. Prior</a> had previously corre=
sponded at some length. Kripke semantics is basically simple, but proofs ar=
e eased using semantic-tableaux or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Analytic_tableaux" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Analytic tableaux">analy=
tic tableaux</a>, as explained by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Evert_Willem_Beth" title=3D"Evert Willem Beth">E. W. Beth</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A._N._Prior" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"A. N. Prior">A. N. Prior</a> created modern <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Temporal_logic" title=3D"Temporal logic">tempora=
l logic</a>, closely related to modal logic, in 1957 by adding modal operat=
ors [F] and [P] meaning "eventually" and "previously". <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vaughan_Pratt" title=3D"Vaughan Pratt">Vaughan Pratt</=
a> introduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dynamic_logic_(modal=
_logic)" title=3D"Dynamic logic (modal logic)">dynamic logic</a> in 1976. I=
n 1977, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amir_Pnueli" title=3D"Amir=
 Pnueli">Amir Pnueli</a> proposed using temporal logic to formalise the beh=
aviour of continually operating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Co=
ncurrent_program" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Concurrent program">concur=
rent programs</a>. Flavors of temporal logic include <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Propositional_dynamic_logic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Propositional dynamic logic">propositional dynamic logic</a> (PDL), (pr=
opositional) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_temporal_logic=
" title=3D"Linear temporal logic">linear temporal logic</a> (LTL), <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computation_tree_logic" title=3D"Computat=
ion tree logic">computation tree logic</a> (CTL), <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Hennessy%E2%80%93Milner_logic" title=3D"Hennessy=E2=80=93Mi=
lner logic">Hennessy=E2=80=93Milner logic</a>, and <i>T</i>.<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<=
i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Please_clarify" title=
=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"Add a wikilink, give a longer =
name, or give a reference for the 'T' logic. (November 2016)">clarification=
 needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The mathematical structure of modal logic, namely <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(structure)" title=3D"Boolean algebr=
a (structure)">Boolean algebras</a> augmented with <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Unary_operation" title=3D"Unary operation">unary operation=
s</a> (often called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_algebra"=
 title=3D"Modal algebra">modal algebras</a>), began to emerge with <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J.C.C._McKinsey" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"J.C.C. McKinsey">J. C. C. McKinsey</a>'s 1941 proof that <i>S2</i> a=
nd <i>S4</i> are decidable,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-42" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modal_logic#cite_note-42"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 and reached full flower in the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Alfred_Tarski" title=3D"Alfred Tarski">Alfred Tarski</a> and his stud=
ent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bjarni_J%C3%B3nsson" title=3D"=
Bjarni J=C3=B3nsson">Bjarni J=C3=B3nsson</a> (J=C3=B3nsson and Tarski 1951=
=E2=80=9352). This work revealed that <i>S4</i> and <i>S5</i> are models of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interior_algebra" title=3D"Interi=
or algebra">interior algebra</a>, a proper extension of Boolean algebra ori=
ginally designed to capture the properties of the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Interior_operator" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Interior =
operator">interior</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closure=
_operator" title=3D"Closure operator">closure operators</a> of <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topology">topology</a>. Tex=
ts on modal logic typically do little more than mention its connections wit=
h the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boolean_algebra_(st=
ructure)" title=3D"Boolean algebra (structure)">Boolean algebras</a> and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topology" title=3D"Topology">topolog=
y</a>. For a thorough survey of the history of formal modal logic and of th=
e associated mathematics, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robe=
rt_Goldblatt" title=3D"Robert Goldblatt">Robert Goldblatt</a> (2006).<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-43" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Modal_logic#cite_note-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
